Original Implementation (Left) vs My Implementation (Right)If you have ever tapped the “Rate Movie” notification on BookMyShow, chances are you have noticed that ridiculously smooth, physics driven slider animation that makes the whole interaction feel instantly alive.
Naturally, my first thought was: “I should build this myself. How hard could it be?”. Turns out, deceptively hard. What starts as a fun little UI experiment quickly snowballs into gesture quirks, animation tuning, edge cases, and a surprising amount of “why is this behaving like that?” moments.
But somewhere between the spring physics and the late-night debugging, it also becomes one of the most satisfying and educational UI components you can build.
Before we begin, here is the complete code in SwiftUI incase you want to refer it 👇
In this article I have shared what I learned by breaking down complex animation, why things randomly fly off the screen (seriously), and how to actually make animations feel good.

The Animation Timeline
If you stare at a really good UI interaction long enough, you realize it’s not just one animation, it’s a carefully choreographed sequence of micro animations. And that’s exactly what I did to build this animation and break the visual experience down into a timeline:

• Phase 1: The Idle State: The rating track sits quietly. A subtle red star rests inside the rating track’s groove.

• Phase 2: The Grab: The moment the user touches the slider, the UI wakes up. The star instantly scales up slightly and pops upward out of the track on the Y-axis so the user’s thumb doesn’t hide it. A small tracking circle appears on the track itself at the position where star was sitting previously.

• Phase 3: The Drag: As the user pulls their finger across the screen, the star follows. But it doesn’t just slide stiffly, it reacts to momentum. If dragged right, the star tilts dynamically to 45 degrees. If dragged left, it tilts to -45 degrees. A slight spring lag gives the star a feeling of physical weight.

• Phase 4: The Release: The user lets go. The star slows down and stops. Crucially, if the star was tilted left, it rotates clockwise directly and crisply back to 0 degrees. If tilted right, it snaps counter-clockwise straight back to 0. Crisp, clean, and intentional.
By breaking the interaction down into these four distinct phases, writing the code became infinitely easier. I just had to build a UI that responded to these specific state changes.

Code it Up!
At its core, the slider is just a GeometryReader containing a ZStack with four main layers: the background track, the active fill track, the tracking circle, and the floating star.
Here is a look at the code driving this interaction:
struct StarSlider: View {
@Binding var rating: Double // 0.0 to 1.0 @State var previousRating: Double = 0
@State var tiltAngle: Double = 0
@State var isSliding: Bool = false
@State var hasInteracted: Bool = false
var body: some View {
GeometryReader { geometry in
let thumbSize: CGFloat = 34
let availableWidth = geometry.size.width - thumbSize
ZStack(alignment: .leading) {
// 1. Background Track
Capsule().fill(Color.gray.opacity(0.3)).frame(height: 8)
// 2. Active Fill Track
Capsule().fill(Color.red)
.frame(width: max(thumbSize/2, CGFloat(rating) * availableWidth + thumbSize/2), height: 8)
// 3. The Tracking Circle
Circle()
.fill(Color.red)
.frame(width: 16, height: 16)
// PHASE 1 & 2: Hidden initially, scales up on interaction
.scaleEffect(hasInteracted ? 1 : 0.001)
.opacity(hasInteracted ? 1 : 0)
.offset(x: CGFloat(rating) * availableWidth + 9)
// 4. The Floating Star
Image(systemName: "star.fill")
.resizable()
.scaledToFit()
.frame(width: thumbSize-8, height: thumbSize-8)
.foregroundColor(.red)
// PHASE 2 & 4: Scales up when sliding, shrinks slightly on release
.scaleEffect(isSliding ? 1.2 : 1.1)
.rotationEffect(.degrees(-tiltAngle), anchor: .bottom)
.offset(
x: CGFloat(rating) * availableWidth + 4,
y: hasInteracted ? -40 : 0 // PHASE 2: Pops upward out of the track
)
// PHASE 3: Heavier spring creates physical weight/lag during tracking
.animation(.spring(response: 0.6, dampingFraction: 0.7), value: rating)
.animation(.spring(response: 0.4, dampingFraction: 0.6), value: tiltAngle)
// PHASE 3: Directional Tracking
.onChange(of: rating) { newValue in
if newValue > previousRating {
tiltAngle = 45 // Dragging right -> Tilt right
} else if newValue < previousRating {
tiltAngle = -45 // Dragging left -> Tilt left
}
previousRating = newValue
}
// PHASE 4: The Clean Release logic
.onChange(of: isSliding) { isSliding in
if !isSliding {
tiltAngle = 0 // Stand back up straight
}
}
}
.frame(height: geometry.size.height, alignment: .center)
.gesture(
DragGesture(minimumDistance: 0)
.onChanged { drag in
// Trigger PHASE 2: The Grab
withAnimation(.spring(response: 0.4, dampingFraction: 0.6)) {
self.hasInteracted = true
}
// Trigger PHASE 3: The Drag math
let dragX = drag.location.x - (thumbSize / 2)
let percentage = dragX / availableWidth
// Guardrails: Clamping the value strictly between 0.0 and 1.0
self.rating = max(0.0, min(1.0, Double(percentage)))
self.isSliding = true
}
.onEnded { drag in
// Trigger PHASE 4: The Release
self.isSliding = false
}
)
}
.frame(height: 100)
}
}
Connecting Code to the timeline we discussed previously:

• Phase 1 (The Idle State) in Code: Look at the initial states of hasInteracted and isSliding, both starting as false. Because of this, the tracking circle's .scaleEffect evaluates to 0.001 (almost hidden), and the star's Y-offset is sitting safely at 0, resting perfectly inside the track line.

• Phase 2 (The Grab) in Code: The magic starts inside DragGesture's .onChanged block. The split second a user's finger touches down, hasInteracted and isSliding flip to true. Instantly, the star's ternary operator for Y-offset shifts to -40, snapping it upward away from the finger, while .scaleEffect(isSliding ? 1.2 : 1.1) balloons its size.

• Phase 3 (The Drag) in Code: As the finger moves, the gesture block calculates the tracking percentage. We pass this to the .onChange(of: rating) block. By comparing newValue against previousRating, our code senses direction. If the values are growing, tiltAngle hits 45, if shrinking, it sets to -45. Because we applied a heavier spring animation (response: 0.6) to the rating value, the star doesn't perfectly match the finger position frame-for-frame and safely lags behind, simulating physical mass.

• Phase 4 (The Release) in Code: When the user lifts their finger, .onEnded kicks in and resets isSliding = false. This directly triggers our second .onChange block. By hard-setting tiltAngle = 0 the moment sliding stops, we bypass the spring's natural desire to sway back and forth like a pendulum. The star returns straight up and down cleanly and sharply.

Mistakes I Made (So You Don’t Have To)
Building this wasn’t entirely smooth sailing. Here are a couple of roadblocks I hit along the way.
1. The Modifier Order Trap: Accidental Orbital Mechanics
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Output with incorrect modifier orderIf you take one single thing away from this article, let it be this: in SwiftUI, modifier order changes everything.
When I first tried to make the star lean into the drag, I accidentally built a solar system simulator. My star was swooping in giant, bizarre arcs across the screen instead of sliding nicely in a straight horizontal line.
Here is why it happens, explained simply. Imagine your UI component is pinned to the screen with a thumbtack:

• Offset first, then Rotate: If you use .offset() to move your view 100 pixels to the right, and then apply a .rotationEffect(), SwiftUI keeps the "thumbtack" at the original starting position and spins the entire coordinate space. Your star swings around on an invisible 100-pixel string like a planet orbiting a sun.

• Rotate first, then Offset: If you apply .rotationEffect() first, the star just spins in place on its own axis. Then, when you apply the .offset(), you push that already-tilted star 100 pixels to the right. It moves along a perfectly straight horizontal path.
To keep the star moving straight while leaning, the .rotationEffect must always happen before the .offset.
2. Killing Magic Numbers with GeometryReader
Early on, hardcoded offsets worked perfectly… until I loaded the app on a different device size. To make the component responsive, GeometryReader is non-negotiable.
By wrapping the slider in a GeometryReader, we can dynamically calculate exactly how much runway the star has based on the actual layout width (let availableWidth = geometry.size.width - thumbSize). From there, positioning the star is just simple percentage math. It scales flawlessly whether it’s on a smaller iPhone or a massive iPad screen, completely eliminating the need to guess screen boundaries.

Final Thoughts
Rebuilding this slider evolved from a simple UI task into a practical exploration of transform hierarchies, responsive layouts, and the power of state-driven animation.
When you break an animation down into a clear timeline and map your code directly to those visual states, you realize that SwiftUI gives you all the tools you need to build world class interactions. Next time you see a bouncy, fluid interaction in an iOS app, take a moment to appreciate the invisible tug of war happening between modifier orders, state properties, and geometry readers just beneath the surface!
Now go build something magical yourself! ✨
